        <section class="main-section" id="JavaScript_and_Java">
            <header>JavaScript and Java</header>
            <p>JavaScript and Java are two different programming languages.</p>
            <p>JavaScript is a client-side language, while Java is a server-side language.</p>
            <p>JavaScript is used for creating interactive web pages, while Java is used for creating enterprise-level applications.</p>
            <code>public class HelloWorld { public static void main(String[] args) { System.out.println("Hello World"); } }</code>
            <ul>
                <li>JavaScript is a client-side language.</li>
                <li>Java is a server-side language.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="main-section" id="Hello_World">
            <header>Hello World</header>
            <p>Hello World is a traditional program to print "Hello World" on the screen.</p>
            <p>It is often used as a "Hello, World!" program, which is a program that prints "Hello, World!" to the screen.</p>
            <p>In JavaScript, you can print "Hello World" using the console.log function.</p>
            <code>console.log("Hello World");</code>
            <ul>
                <li>Hello World in JavaScript.</li>
                <li>Hello World in Java.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="main-section" id="Variables">
            <header>Variables</header>
            <p>Variables are used to store values.</p>
            <p>In JavaScript, you can declare a variable using the let, const, or var keyword.</p>
            <p>Variables can be of different data types, such as number, string, boolean, etc.</p>
            <p>In Java, you can declare a variable using the data type followed by the variable name.</p>
            <code>let x = 10;</code>
            <ul>
                <li>Variable declaration.</li>
                <li>Variable assignment.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
        <section class="main-section" id="Data_Types">
            <header>Data Types</header>
            <p>Data types are used to define the type of a variable.</p>
            <p>In JavaScript, there are several data types, including number, string, boolean, null, undefined, etc.</p>
            <p>In Java, there are several data types, including int, double, boolean, char, etc.</p>
            <p>Data types are important because they determine the type of operations that can be performed on a variable.</p>
            <code>let x = 10; // number</code>
            <ul>
                <li>Number data type.</li>
                <li>String data type.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
